{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_galena_ver01/data/sn88051124/00516990211/1908040301/0108.xml":{"full_text":"The Echo Gives The\nLatest and most Re\nliable mining news.\nNO. 51.\nVOL. 21.\nYELLVILLE. IVIARION COUNTY, ARKANSAS, FRIDAY, APRIL 3, 1908.\nJohn H. Woods. S. W. Woods\nWOODS BROTHERS,\nattorneys-at-law,\nand Solicitors In Chancery.\n(Successors to S. W. Woods.)\nWill practice in all the State and .Federal Courts\nand before the U. S. Land Office. Prompt at\ntention fflren to all business entrusted to their\ncare.\nNT Office\u2014Over Bank of Yellville.\nY ellvuxe, Arkansas.\nT. M. Seatvel. W. R. JorCES. A. C. Sea wet..\nSEA WE L, JONES SEAWKL,\nAttorneys-at-Law\nYELLVILLE. AKKANSAS.\nOffice\u2014Up Stairs In Berry Block.\nPhono No. 45. _\nWill practice In nil courts both State\nand Federal and U. S. Land Office.\nJ. C. FLOYD.\nAttorney-at-Law,\nAnd Solicitor In Chancery.\nPrompt attention will be given to all\nbadness entrusted to his care.\nYELLVILLE.\nARK.\nL. M. DUREN,\nAttorney-at-Law,\nAXD\nREAL ESTATE AGENT.\nI list, and pay taxes.\nOffice on oornor of D and Carter Streets\nYELLVILLE ARK.\nALLYN' SMITH,\nYellville _\nCottbr, 1 ARKANSES.\nS. t. BBOOKSHKR. t. M. WBAST.\nBrooksher Weast,\nPhyeielaiiH Sc Siirifeonw,\nOffice over Hardware Store',\nYELLVILLE, ABK.\nW, C. Wilson,-^\nPHYSICIAN and SURGEON,\nOffice on Main Street in\nBuilding formerly occu\npied by Brooksher Weast\nPhone No. 79.\nYELLVILLE, ARKANSAS.\n_t_\u2014\nJ. Thompson,\nPHYSICIAN SURGEON\nOffice on West Main Street.\nPhone No. 57.\nYELLVILLE, ARK.\nW. L. SEAWEL,\nU. S. Mineral Surveyor,\nYeiaville. Ark.,\nWill do enffineertn? work in the entire mineral\nbelt and alao hare some bargains in mineral\nlands.\nIf you want the best\nACCIDENT OR HEALTH\nINSURANCE.\nCall on, W. B. MATTHEWSON,\nY ELLVILLE, APKANSAS\nL. T. MEDLEY,\nJeweler and\nOptician.\nALL WORK GUARANTEED.\nSOUTH SIDE PUBLIC SQUARE,\nYELLVILLE, ARKANSAS.\nHave your old shoos made new at\nR. A. TATUM S\nshoe jl3jto TiTZPJLm shop.\n4\u00a7F* Terras Strictly Cash.\nPresident E osevelt Says\nthat outdoor exercise is needed\nby the American people. That\nis alf very weH, but how can peo\nple with rheumatism follow that\nadvise? The answer is simple\n\u2014use Ballard\u2019s Snow Liniment\nand the the rheumatism will go;\nleaving you as spry as a colt.\nGives 4u'ck and permanent re\nlief frdm rheumatism, neuralgia,\nlathe back and all pains. Sold bv\nCope Drug Co.\nA BABY SHOW IS YELLYILLE\nwould baye many contestants;\nbut it is safe to say that the\nhealthiest baby would win the\nprize. No baby can be healthy\nwho suffers from worms and\nmost babies do unless they are\nkept free from them with White\u2019s\nCream Vermifuge. Acts quick\n'ly, yet mildly\u2014is its own purga\ntire. Mothers don\u2019t attempt to\nraise children without White\u2019s\nCream Vermifuge. Price 25cts,\nSold by Cope Drug Co.'\nTHE EGHO\u2019S\nMONTHLY MINING BULLETIN\nFor The Month of March.\nThe month of March has witnessed more political than in\ndustrial activity in Marion county, but notwithstanding that fact,\nthe mining interest has, come in for a liberal share of attention\nfrom operators living on the outside and the record of develop\nment has not been allowed to drop back. Without attempting to\nelaborate on the operations here during the past month, the\nEcho will for the present give only a synopsis of the leading\nmining news of the Yellville district for the month just closed.\nWork was resumed by the Schell Mining Company on\ntheir lease at the Golconda, in the Kingdon Springs camp, after\nMr. Joe Schell the manager had returned from a visit to Ft.\nSmith where he had gone to confer with other members of his\ncompany regarding the future policy of operations. It will be\nremembered that these people took the lease on this property\nafter it had been drilled and on the strength of the record of\nthe drill, which went to show that a paying ore body had been\ntapped. After sinking a prospect shaft a little over 100 feet\ndeep, they found the drill record verified to their satisfaction,\nand are now at work with a view to opening up the mine for\nactive operation.\nThe shaft at the Ere-Ozark, which is being put down in\nthe midst of three drill holes, forming a triangle and some 200\nfeet apart, is now down near the 100 foot level, having encount\nered very rich ore as indicated by the drill Records.\nSupt Dexter of the Bonanza mine in the Buffalo City\ncamp is pushing work with a force of about thirty men and has\nhis 150 ton mill nearly completed. One of the 80 horse power\nboilers is now in place and the other one soon will be. He has a\ndouble shift of men at work in the ground, sinking the main\nshaft, in order to be ready for regular mining when the mill is\ncompleted, Mr Bridget, who has charge of the construction of\nthe plant, is an old mill builder and statas that the mill he is put\nting up here is at the richest Zinc mine he ever put a mill on.\nHis experience has been largely in the Joplin district.\nThe Iola mine, which was a short time ago bought out\nright by the leasges, is in operation, keeping the mill going a\ngood part of the time. The main tunnel, driven in on the ore\nledge, extends back into the mountain 476 feet and presents a\nten foot working face of ore that runs five to seven per cent\nconcentrates. Cross cuts are run out from the main tunnels un\ntil now it is estimated that they have 9000 tons of pay ore block\ned out, ready to be removed. Additional drills and air com\npressors are to be installed, preparatoiy to increasing the work\ning force in the ground.\nConsiderable prospecting has been done in the Short\nMountain Camp, near Monarch, during the month and some\nvery good finds reported. This locality shows some of the\nheaviest lead deposits so far discovered in this field. The quan\ntity of float lead found there is remarkable and in the opioion of\nexperienced miners, is an evidence of still greater bodies than\nyet have been uncovered there.\nT. Paradis who has been doing considerbble development\nwork on the Cantrell property near Dodd City, which he bought\nlast fall, recently closed the purchase of a 40 acre tract of very\nfine zinc land, adjoining the Pilot Rock and which he will devel\nop at once. It is his purpose to also continue development on\nthe 240 acres mentioned which is showing up very fine.\nThe Pilot Rock, near Dodd City, was the scene of one of\nthe richest ore strikes last week that has yet been recorded in\nthis district. The miners driving the north heading, broke into\na body of fine jack, covering the entire face of the tunnel and\nwhile to the casual observer, appears to be at least three fourths\nore, it is conservatively estimated to run fifty per cent concen\ntrates. Work is also in progress in the east heading of the tun\nnel and while the ore there is not so rich as in the other, it is\ngood pay dirt, and the little mill is going most of the tiine. At\npresent the plant consists of only a crusher and set of rolls with\nhand jigs. The capacity of the plant will be increased' as the\ndevelopment of the ore body and working room for the miners,\nwill justify. They have a car load of ore in the bins, ready for\nshipme?K!\nW'1^16 Madison mine, near Zinc, resumed operations last\nwe^K* TJiere a fine ore body is developed and the mine is euqip\nped with a modem mill.\n\"t:v' Oil ley and Sandalls have opened up a rich body of lead on\nthe Ben Harrison lease in the Dodd City camp and are now at\nwork, taking out a large quantity of free ore.\nUnless present plans fail to materialize, we will be in\nposition to give the readers of the Echo news of special interest\nregarding important mining transactions in our next Bulletin..\nTHE ECHO\u2019S MINING DEPARTMENT\nGATHERED FROM OPERATORS AND OTHERS.\nEd Zimmerman of Harrison,\naccompanied by; a party of\nstrangers, passed through town\nWednesday, enroute to the\nRush camp.\nThe Erie-Ozark and Schell\nmining company continue to\npush development work on their\nrespective properties in the\nKingdon Springs camp.\nGilley and Company are go\ning ahead with development\nwork on their lease at the Ben\nHarrison, where they have\nopened up a large body of ore.\nThe shaft at the Bonanza is\nnow down between 80 and 90\nfeet. The first 58 feet was\nsunk under direction of W. H.\nTripp in about six weeks work\ning a double shift of men.\nW. F. Cleveland has retnmed\nfrom Harlin Iowa and we un\nderstand, expects to start up\nthe Monkey Hill soon, however\noperations there for the present!\nwill probably depend on the ore\nmarket.\nNote the new propsitions pre\nsented on 4th page by J. H.\nHand\u2019s Real Estate Agency. If\nyou are interested in securing a\nfirst class mining investment,\nit will pay you to investigate\neither of them.\nThe Echos statement last\nweek in regard to the Bonanza\nboiler which fell off the barge\ninto the river, having been\nabondoned for the present, was\nan error. We have since learn\ned that the boiler has been tak\nen from the river and is now on\nthe road to the mine where it\nwill be installed in the mill\nwhich is nedring completion.\nW. T. Williams was over from\nDodd City Tuesday and reports\nwork progressing satisfactori\n$20,000 Damages.\nIn the suit of Mrs. Luie\nFreeman agaiost the Iron Moun\ntain Railroad Company for the\nrecovery of $50,000 damages on\naccount of the death of her hus\nband, Cbas. Freeman, an engin\neer who was killed in a ufreqk\nnear Crickett the 8th of last De\ncember, the Jury returned a ver\ndict in favor of the plaintiff last\nMonday for $20,000. 'The plan\ntiff was represented by Seawel,\nJones Seawel of this place and\nO. T. Hamlin of Spriugfield and\nthe defense by Horton South\nI of Mountain Home. The argu\nmen ts of the attorneys consumed\nmost of the day Monday and the\nverdict was returned within two\nhours after the case went to the\nJnry.\nKnickerbocker Bank Reopen*.\nNew York, March 26.-^Mark\ning another decided step toward\nI the return of prosperity to the\nally at the Pilot Rock. He stat\ned that they expect to finish\ncleaning up a car load of con\ncentrates this week. He also\ninformed us that things are\nmoving along in an energetic\nmanner at the Iola, since the\npurchase of the property by the\nleasees.\nJudge D. W. Csve of Zinc\npassed through town Sunday\non his way to Rush, accompan\nied by his nephew, T. R. Cave\nof Manhattan Kansas, who\nwent down to start work on the\nHoodlum which joins the Zinc\nBasin on Clabber creek. This\nproperty was drilled last year\nby J. C. Fain and heavy ore\nruns were reported to exist be\nlow the level of the valley.\nMr. Tim Estes, practical\nmine operator in the Joplin dis\ntrict, arrived here Tuesday. Mr.\nEstes says that with the ten\njrears active experience that he\nhas had as a mine operator in\nthe Joplin district, and what he j\nknows about the Yellville dis-1\ntrict, he has made up his. mind\nto cast his lot with the later.\nHe says that while it is not gen\nerally known, yet it is neverthe\nless a fact that not more than\none mine out of every forty in\nthat district will pay a profit\nover operating expenses when\nthe price of ore is below $40\nper ton, even with all the mod\nem equipment and the best\nmining-skill that can be obtain\ned. He is of the opinion that\nwith ample capital for develop\nment purposes, as they all must\nhave there, and the same equip\nment and practical management\nthat are employed there, the\nYellvilie distriet would double\ndiscount the Joplin district for\ndividends to eperators. There\nJ fore he decided to tie up to the\nYellville district.\nmetropolis the Knickerbocker\nTrust Company, which closed its\ndoors last October, was reopen\ned for business at noon today.\nThe bank has assests of over $50\n000,000, with liabilities slightly\nless, and there is every likeli\nI hood it will be able to pay .all of\nthe 20,000 depositors in full.\nThe reopening of the Knicker\nbocker Trust Company, in ac\ncordance with the plans for its\nrehabilitation, prepared after\nfour months\u2019 labor by a commit\ntee of depositors, released to the\ncommunity assets aggregating\n$46,370,620.\n\u2018The reopening of the Knick\nbocker Trust Company,\u201d declar\ned Janies Russell Seely of the\ncounsel for the depositors\u2019 com*\nmittee, \u2022\u2018will have a stimulating1\neffect not only upon the local fin\nancial situation, but upon every\nfinancial center on the globe. It\nis the best thing that has hap\npened since the panic.\u201d\nJudge Clarke, is dessmissing\nthe temporary receivers of the\nsuspended trust company and\nsigned the resumption order\nspoke in commendatory vein of\nthe work of the depositors\u2019 com*\nmitte, counsel and 'others who\nhad labored so assiduously in\nworking out the rehabilitation\nplan.\nUnder the terms of this plan\nthe Knickerbocker Trust Com*\npany will not receive their de\nposits in full when the trust com-\npany opens its doors, but will re\nceive 10 per cent today if tbe\u00a3\nwantitar.d the remaining por\ntions of the deposit's can be with\ndrawn at interyals conveying a\nperiod of about two and one^hllf\nyears.\nThe Kew t'onnty Central Committee.\nAt the primary on the 25th of*\nMarch, the following- committed\nmen were elected to serve on the\nMarion county Democratic Cen\ntral Committee for the next two\nyears, to-wit: Committeeman at\nLarge for Marion county, J. H.\nHand; Union township, S. W.'\nWoods; Dodd City, W. H. Chaf\nfin; Summit, J. B. Rowden; De\nSoto, Mark Hears; Jefferson.D.'\nE. Melton; Big Creek, Fred BS\nSanders; Buffalo, T. P. Tilleys\nCrooked Creek, J. F. Horner;\nWhite River, T. H. Flipping/\nJas. Creek, Dink Berry; North r\nFork, E/ T. Record; Cedir!\nCreek; N. B. Day; Blyeth, J. P.\nBrady; Prairie, F. A. Lowery1; 1\nHampton, J. L. McCarty; Bear-\nden, N. J. Bearden. -The other t\ntownships in the county did.not\nelect committeemen.\nCall For a Republican County Con\nvention. 'V\nIiraccordance with the resolu-\ntions adopted by the Marion*\ncounty Republican Central Com-\nmittee at its meeting on Dec.\n12th 1907, a County Convention V\nof delegates from the townships\nin Marion county will be held in i\nthe court bouse in Yellyille, Ar-V\nKansas, on Saturday April 18th,\n1903 for the purpose of electing\nthree delegates and three alter\nnates to attend the Republican\nState Convention at Hot Springs,\nArkansas, on April 23th, 1908, to\nelect delegates to the 3rd dis\ntrict congressional convention,\nto elect delegates to the convert**\ntion of the 14th Judicial district,\nto elect a member of the State\ncentral committee, a,nd to trans\nact such other business as may\nproperly come before said con\nvention.\nThe following appointment of\ndelegates frond the several town*\nships was made by the Central\ncommittee at its meeting afore*\nsaid.* i\nNorth Fork 4; Cedar Creek 3;\nKeesee 1; Crockett 2; Franklin 4;\nSugar Loaf 1; James Creek 3;\nBlythe 2; Prairie 4; Hamptou 7;\nLiberty 3; DeSoto 3; Big Creek\n1; Jefferson Be; -1-\ned Creeu i; Boff.iU. \u25a0,;,j f:'tef\nRiver 2; Water Creed 2; ^v4dt#\nCity 3; Summits; Union 7.\nAll delegates are urgently re*.\nquested to be present at sard\nconvention.\nB. F. Bcrnks, Secretary.\nV. A. Wilber, Chair mao,.\nCard of Thanks,\nKingdom Springs, Ark; v\nMarch 28th, 190S..\nEditor Echo,\nDear Sir:\u2014If yon will,allow me\nspace in your paper I wish to\nexpress my heart-felt thanks to\nthe good citizens who so earnest-\nlv supported ihe in my race for\nSheriff, I have no excuse\nredder for my shortage except!\nthat I did not get votes enough\u00bb<\nSo hurrah for John Nanny.\nRespt, W. H. Wuigate;\nSubscribe for the MouNTAbt\nEcho and get all the mining\nnews from the North Arkanscs\nzinc field.y<:","height":"24608","width":"17020"}}
